         I have no idea what you're talking about.</P><P>Closed Bnet servers for Diablo II nowadays are in many ways free from any form of cheating whatsoever.  As fast as the hackers may turn out their little map and dupe hacks, they can't beat the fact that Blizzard _permanently_ flags a player as a cheater once they're caught (and a lot of them have been caught), and forces those players to either buy a new game or only play in cheater infested games for the rest of their life.</P><P>Besides, Diablo II is not a MMORPG, but WoW will be.  MMORPGs handle almost everything through the server, therefore they are pretty hard to hack.  The best hackers could do to EQ so far is to make something that scans packets as they are coming in and shows where monsters are and what loot they have, how much exp they give, etc.  Knowing Blizzard, they'd probably have a even better security system against hackers than VI.  That is not to say that the game will be completely hack free - because hackers are in some ways the smartest and most persistent people on earth, but don't count on Blizzard turning a blind eye on cheaters.</P><P><BR>Etadanik the Redeemed<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
