         quote<BR>"I have no idea what you're talking about."</P><P><BR>ok, here is what im talking about<BR>map hacks first of all, were huge, since dungeons were random maps, instead of spending 10 mins looking for a exit to the next level, it took 10 secs to run/teleport to it<BR>that means that it was WAY more efficient to go after boss mobs<BR>but that wasnt the big problem</P><P><BR>The problem was that there were items that were so ridiculously rare, that on a whole server, there would maybe be 5-10 of them, some of the higher level runes, for example(as the game was designed)</P><P>what happened was that duping allowed people to take anything they wanted, and make unlimited #'s of them.  they could then trade these items for other items, and dupe them, basically destorying the economy by counterfieting money at will.<BR>This is analagous to 1% of the population having a printing press at home printing up 100's...how would you feel if you had to go to work every day to make something that they made in seconds?</P><P>and you say that blizzard was banning players, and making them play in "cheater infested games"  i dont know where you came up with this, but there are no separate cheater infested games.  I think you may be confused with open-battlenet, which is where you can play with your characters that are stored on your harddrive.  These games are full of players with duped/made up items, since anyone can download char editors that are so simple a monkey could run them, and create players with more stats and better gear than you could get in the game.</P><P>In blizards closed battlenet, they handled everythign thru the server also, and if you dont think that there were ridiculous amounts of dupes, then you didnt play the high end game too much.</P><P>I played D2 for a couple of years, and I had 5 players at level 80 before the xpac, which was ridiculously hard to do, and pst xpac i had 8 players at90+, so i know what im talking about.  The items that were being traded for next to nothing were very rare, and there were obviously too many of them in the game.</P><P>It would be nice if Blizzard finally figured out that letting people cheat like mad ruined their games, but i doubt it, since they still havent released the patch they promised months ago that will set up new chars who cant trade with old chars, supposedly to make a new economy for people who dont want to cheat.</P><P>Edit</P><P>ok, after i posted this, i popped over to diabloii.net, and here is an exercpt message directly from blizzard</P><P>"With Ith items be deleted in v1.10?<BR>Ith Items are made with a hack, and have been very heavily duped.  They are described in some detail on our warnings page.  Blizzard would have to modify how the game checks Runewords to make it able to detect Ith items, (they aren't checked for dupes like rares and uniques) and as far as we know Blizzard isn't going to do the work necessary to implement Ith detection.  If they could just flick a button and delete all of them, I'm sure they would, but it's more difficult than that, unfortunately."</P><P>notice the "very heavily duped"</P><P></P><P>Edited by - zikuofkarana on 07/15/2002  23:06:34<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
